	11
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
</P>
</DIV>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-LEFT:10.2941176470588%;MARGIN-RIGHT:10.2941176470588%;">
<HR ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE='BACKGROUND-COLOR:#000000; BORDER-WIDTH:0; COLOR:#000000; HEIGHT:2PT; LINEHEIGHT:0; WIDTH:100%;'>
<P STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage12"></A>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-LEFT:10.2941176470588%;MARGIN-RIGHT:10.2941176470588%;">
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 30PT;COLOR:#0563C1;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<A HREF="#AXSM-20151231X10KA_HTM_TOC">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;COLOR:#0563C1;">
	Table of Contents
</FONT>
</A>
</P>
</DIV>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-LEFT:10.2941176470588%;MARGIN-RIGHT:10.2941176470588%;">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Indication Overview
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	CLBP is defined as persistent or fluctuating low back pain lasting at least three months. It is a disabling and costly condition that is associated with increased healthcare utilization. The economic costs of CLBP are estimated to range from $12.2&nbsp;billion to $90.6&nbsp;billion annually in the United States. Factors that contribute to this economic impact include prolonged loss of function, consequent loss of work productivity, treatment costs, and disability payments. Low back pain may be due to a specific cause such as fracture, tumor, infection, or nerve root compression. However it is estimated that in more than 85% of cases such specific causes cannot be identified, resulting in the majority of cases being classified as non
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;specific.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	Recently, it has been suggested that patients with MCs may represent a specific clinical subgroup of CLBP patients. MCs are vertebral bone marrow changes that are visible on MRI of the spine, and that represent regions of increased bone turnover and pro
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;inflammatory mediators. MCs are classified into types&nbsp;1, 2, or 3, based on radiographic and histological features. MCs are clinically relevant because they are associated with low back pain, based on published studies. Findings from studies in clinical and non
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;clinical populations have demonstrated that the presence of MCs, especially type&nbsp;1 MCs, is correlated with low back pain, predicts persistent symptoms, and sick leaves, and is associated with poor outcomes. These studies therefore suggest that MCs are a potential target for pharmaceutical intervention.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	There is currently no therapy specifically approved by the FDA or the EMA to treat CLBP associated with MCs. Currently available therapy for the broader CLBP population includes non
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;pharmacological approaches, such as exercise, and pharmacological treatments, such as NSAIDs and opioid medications. Current pharmacological treatments are generally short
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;acting and may address the symptoms of CLBP, but are not thought to have an effect on the underlying cause of the condition.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	Results of epidemiological studies suggest that there are approximately 121&nbsp;million adults in the United States with low back pain in a given year. Approximately 9&nbsp;million of these sufferers are estimated to have CLBP, of whom we estimate approximately 1.6&nbsp;million have type&nbsp;1 MCs.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Rationale for the Use of AXS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	&#8209;02 in CLBP Associated with MCs
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	The rationale for utilizing AXS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;02 for the treatment of CLBP associated with MCs is based on the observations that (1)&nbsp;MCs are associated with low back pain, (2)&nbsp;MCs represent regions of increased bone turnover based on three
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;phase bone scans and increased pro
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;inflammatory cytokines and vascular density based on analysis of lesions resected from human subjects, and (3)&nbsp;zoledronic acid potently inhibits bone turnover, may reduce pro
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;inflammatory cytokine production, is anti
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;angiogenic, and localizes preferentially to regions of increased turnover. The pharmacological actions of zoledronic acid therefore suggest the potential for AXS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;02 to affect MCs, thereby reducing pain in patients with CLBP associated with MCs.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Clinical Development of AXS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	&#8209;02
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	We are developing AXS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;02 and intend to seek FDA approval for the product candidate utilizing the 505(b)(2) regulatory pathway. Section&nbsp;505(b)(2) of the FDCA permits an applicant to file an NDA that relies, in part, on data not developed by or for the applicant and to which the applicant has not received a right of reference, such as the FDA&#x2019;s findings of safety and efficacy in the approval of a similar drug, or reference listed drug, or published literature, in support of its application. We currently plan to rely on the FDA&#x2019;s prior finding of safety and efficacy for IV
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;administered zoledronic acid as well as published literature to support our marketing application.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
</P>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-LEFT:10.2941176470588%;MARGIN-RIGHT:10.2941176470588%;">
<P>
<FONT SIZE="1">
</FONT>
</P>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:24PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	12
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
</P>
</DIV>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-LEFT:10.2941176470588%;MARGIN-RIGHT:10.2941176470588%;">
<HR ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE='BACKGROUND-COLOR:#000000; BORDER-WIDTH:0; COLOR:#000000; HEIGHT:2PT; LINEHEIGHT:0; WIDTH:100%;'>
<P STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage13"></A>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-LEFT:10.2941176470588%;MARGIN-RIGHT:10.2941176470588%;">
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 30PT;COLOR:#0563C1;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<A HREF="#AXSM-20151231X10KA_HTM_TOC">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;COLOR:#0563C1;">
	Table of Contents
</FONT>
</A>
</P>
</DIV>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-LEFT:10.2941176470588%;MARGIN-RIGHT:10.2941176470588%;">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	We held a Type&nbsp;C meeting with the FDA in June&nbsp;2014 where we presented our clinical development plan for AXS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;02 in the treatment of pain associated with CRPS, the pain of knee OA associated with BMLs, and CLBP associated with MCs. Based on feedback from this meeting and other ongoing communications with the FDA, we plan to conduct two Phase&nbsp;3 trials with AXS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;02 in the treatment of pain associated with recently diagnosed CRPS, as well as a toxicology study and a food
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;effect study, to support an NDA filing for this indication. We requested scientific advice and protocol assistance from the EMA for the development of AXS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;02 for the treatment of pain associated with CRPS. We received final advice from the EMA in March&nbsp;2015. Based on this advice, we believe that only one successful Phase&nbsp;3 trial in CRPS will be required to support a Marketing Authorization Application, or MAA, for AXS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;02 in this indication.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	In May&nbsp;2013, we received Orphan Drug Designation from the FDA for AXS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;02 for the treatment of CRPS. This designation may entitle AXS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;02 to a period of seven years of marketing exclusivity for the treatment of CRPS in the United States upon FDA approval. We submitted an Investigational New Drug Application, or IND, sponsored by us, in October 2013 for AXS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;02 for the treatment of pain associated with CRPS.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	In October&nbsp;2013, we received Orphan Medicinal Product Designation from the EMA for AXS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;02 for the treatment of CRPS. Orphan Medicinal Product Designation provides ten years of potential market exclusivity in the European Union if the designated product candidate is approved for the indication for which it is designated and the orphan designation is maintained. Additionally, if a Pediatric Investigation Plan is completed, an additional two years of exclusivity in the European Union could be granted for a product with Orphan Medicinal Product Designation.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	In August&nbsp;2014, we received Fast Track designation from the FDA for AXS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;02 for the treatment of pain associated with CRPS. The FDA&#x2019;s Fast Track designation program is designed to aid in the development and expedite the review of drugs that are intended to treat serious or life
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;threatening conditions. In order to receive Fast Track designation, a product candidate must also demonstrate the potential to address an unmet medical need. Fast Track designation provides greater access to, and more frequent communication with, the FDA throughout the entire drug development and review process, with the goal of getting important new drugs to patients more rapidly. It also provides the opportunity to submit sections of an NDA on a rolling basis, where the FDA may review portions of the NDA as they are received instead of waiting for the entire NDA submission. In addition, Fast Track designated product candidates may be eligible for priority review at the time of NDA submission.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	In October 2015, we reached agreement with the FDA regarding an SPA on the design of a Phase&nbsp;3 clinical trial with AXS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;02 for the treatment of the pain of knee OA associated with BMLs. An SPA documents the FDA&#x2019;s agreement that the design and planned analysis of a clinical trial adequately address scientific and regulatory objectives that, if met, would support a regulatory submission for approval of a drug.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	We completed oral toxicology studies in the rat and dog models to support the dosing of AXS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;02 in our completed Phase&nbsp;1 trial and in our ongoing and planned Phase&nbsp;3 trials. Dose
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;limiting adverse effects were primarily gastrointestinal related. We have completed a Phase&nbsp;1 trial of AXS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;02 to characterize the pharmacokinetics of zoledronic acid and its effects on markers of bone resorption after oral administration of AXS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;02. In this trial, oral administration of AXS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;02 tablets resulted in rapid absorption of zoledronic acid and marked suppression of bone resorption markers.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	The potential effect of zoledronic acid on the pain of knee OA associated with BMLs has been demonstrated in a Phase&nbsp;2, investigator
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;initiated, randomized, double
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;blind, placebo
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;controlled trial. In this trial, IV administration of zoledronic acid resulted in a statistically significant reduction in pain and BML size at 6&nbsp;months. The potential effect of zoledronic acid in CLBP associated with MCs has been demonstrated in a Phase&nbsp;2, investigator
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;initiated, randomized, double
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;blind, placebo
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;controlled trial. In this trial, IV administration of zoledronic acid resulted in statistically significant reductions in pain at 1&nbsp;month and NSAID use at 12&nbsp;months. We have obtained exclusive rights to the data generated from this trial in CLBP.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
</P>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-LEFT:10.2941176470588%;MARGIN-RIGHT:10.2941176470588%;">
<P>
<FONT SIZE="1">
</FONT>
</P>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:24PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	13
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
</P>
</DIV>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-LEFT:10.2941176470588%;MARGIN-RIGHT:10.2941176470588%;">
<HR ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE='BACKGROUND-COLOR:#000000; BORDER-WIDTH:0; COLOR:#000000; HEIGHT:2PT; LINEHEIGHT:0; WIDTH:100%;'>
<P STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage14"></A>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-LEFT:10.2941176470588%;MARGIN-RIGHT:10.2941176470588%;">
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 30PT;COLOR:#0563C1;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<A HREF="#AXSM-20151231X10KA_HTM_TOC">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;COLOR:#0563C1;">
	Table of Contents
</FONT>
</A>
</P>
</DIV>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-LEFT:10.2941176470588%;MARGIN-RIGHT:10.2941176470588%;">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	We are currently conducting a randomized, double
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;blind, placebo
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;controlled Phase&nbsp;3 trial of AXS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;02 in patients with CRPS. We plan to initiate a Phase&nbsp;3 trial in patients with knee OA and BMLs in the first quarter of&nbsp;2016, and a Phase&nbsp;3 trial in patients with CLBP associated with MCs in the fourth quarter of&nbsp;2016 or the first quarter of 2017. We believe our planned Phase&nbsp;3 dosing of AXS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;02 will provide cumulative systemic exposure of zoledronic acid that is similar to that achieved with the 5&nbsp;mg IV dose used in the Phase&nbsp;2 trials in knee OA and CLBP, based on the results of our completed Phase&nbsp;1 trial.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Completed Phase&nbsp;1 Trial of AXS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	&#8209;02
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	We conducted a Phase&nbsp;1 trial to assess the fasting pharmacokinetics, pharmacodynamics, safety, and tolerability of orally administered AXS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;02 tablets in healthy adult male and postmenopausal female volunteers under a Health Canada Clinical Trial Application. The trial was a randomized, open
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;label, partial crossover study in a total of 36 subjects. Each subject received two of the following four treatments: three varying oral doses of AXS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;02 or a 1&nbsp;mg IV dose of zoledronic acid. Each treatment was separated by a wash
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;out period of at least 14&nbsp;days. Blood samples were collected prior to dosing and after dosing to measure zoledronic acid plasma concentrations and the effect of AXS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;02 on biomarkers of bone resorption, including serum CTx.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	Zoledronic acid was rapidly absorbed after oral administration of AXS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;02 tablets with median time to reach the maximum plasma concentration, or T
</FONT>
<SUB STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	max
</SUB>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	, of 30&nbsp;to 45&nbsp;minutes. The absolute oral bioavailability of zoledronic acid after administration of AXS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;02 tablets found in this trial was greater than that reported for oral bisphosphonate agents currently marketed in the United States, based on FDA package inserts. Zoledronic acid plasma concentrations after oral administration of AXS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;02, measured using area under the plasma concentration curve, or AUC, and maximum plasma concentration, or C
</FONT>
<SUB STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	max
</SUB>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	, were found to be dose proportional in the range tested using the power model.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	Oral administration of AXS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;02 resulted in marked reductions of biomarkers of bone resorption. For example, levels of serum CTx were reduced by approximately 80 to 90% seven days after dosing. This effect was generally maintained 14&nbsp;to 15&nbsp;days after dosing.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	There were no reported serious adverse events in the trial. The majority of treatment
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;emergent adverse events experienced were graded as mild or moderate in severity, were transient in nature, and were completely resolved by the end of the study. The most commonly reported adverse events were headache, fever, musculoskeletal pain, diarrhea, abdominal pain, nausea, myalgia, and chills. Adverse events were reported more frequently with increasing oral doses, and more frequently in the oral dose groups than in the IV dose group.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Phase&nbsp;2 of Zoledronic Acid in the Pain of Knee OA Associated with BMLs
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	IV
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;administered zoledronic acid, the active molecule in AXS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;02, was tested in an investigator
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;initiated, single
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;center, randomized, double
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;blind, placebo
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;controlled trial in patients with knee OA and BMLs. In this trial, zoledronic acid treatment reduced pain and BML size, as further described below, demonstrating an effect on symptom and structure. The design and results of this trial have been reported in a peer
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;reviewed journal.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	In the trial, 59&nbsp;patients, aged&nbsp;50 to 80&nbsp;years, with clinical knee OA and knee BMLs on MRI were randomized in a 1:1&nbsp;ratio to receive either a single 5
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;mg IV infusion of zoledronic acid or placebo. BMLs were determined using proton density
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;weighted fat saturation magnetic resonance images at baseline, 6,&nbsp;and 12&nbsp;months. Pain intensity was measured at baseline, 3, 6,&nbsp;and 12&nbsp;months using a 100
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;mm visual analogue scale, or VAS, which is a standard clinical measurement for pain severity. Total BML area was measured in square millimeters at baseline, 6,&nbsp;and 12&nbsp;months. The primary outcomes were the change from baseline to 6&nbsp;months in pain intensity as measured by the VAS, and maximal area of BML measured at 6&nbsp;months. Participants were allowed to remain on their background pain medications but the dose was kept constant through the trial period where possible. One subject randomized to placebo received zoledronic acid. Therefore, data for this patient was included in the zoledronic acid arm in the analyses and results discussed below. This analysis is referred to as a per protocol analysis.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
</P>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-LEFT:10.2941176470588%;MARGIN-RIGHT:10.2941176470588%;">
<P>
<FONT SIZE="1">
</FONT>
</P>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:24PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	14
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
</P>
</DIV>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-LEFT:10.2941176470588%;MARGIN-RIGHT:10.2941176470588%;">
<HR ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE='BACKGROUND-COLOR:#000000; BORDER-WIDTH:0; COLOR:#000000; HEIGHT:2PT; LINEHEIGHT:0; WIDTH:100%;'>
<P STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage15"></A>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-LEFT:10.2941176470588%;MARGIN-RIGHT:10.2941176470588%;">
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 30PT;COLOR:#0563C1;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<A HREF="#AXSM-20151231X10KA_HTM_TOC">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;COLOR:#0563C1;">
	Table of Contents
</FONT>
</A>
</P>
</DIV>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-LEFT:10.2941176470588%;MARGIN-RIGHT:10.2941176470588%;">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	At baseline, the mean VAS score was 54&nbsp;mm. There was a statistically significant reduction in pain intensity, measured using the VAS, from baseline to 6&nbsp;months in the zoledronic acid
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;treated group as compared to placebo, using the per protocol analysis. Changes in pain intensity between baseline and the other time points were numerically greater in the zoledronic acid arm than in the placebo arm but were not statistically significant.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	T
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	here was a statistically significant reduction in BML area at 6&nbsp;months in the zoledronic acid
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;treated group as compared to placebo. At the 12&nbsp;month assessment, the changes in BML size were lower in magnitude in the zoledronic acid arm as compared to the placebo arm and were not statistically significant.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	The most commonly reported adverse events were acute phase reactions, which are primarily cold or flu
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;like symptoms and headaches. Adverse events occurred more frequently in the zoledronic acid
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;treated group. Serious adverse events were primarily non
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;elective hospital admissions, none of which were considered causally related to study drug.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Phase&nbsp;2 of Zoledronic Acid in CLBP Associated with MCs
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	IV
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;administered zoledronic acid was tested in an investigator
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;initiated, single
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;center, randomized, double
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;blind, placebo
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;controlled trial in patients with CLBP associated with MCs. In this trial, zoledronic acid treatment resulted in statistically significant reductions in pain at 1&nbsp;month and NSAID use at 12&nbsp;months. We have exclusive rights to reference these trial data.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	In the trial, 40&nbsp;patients, with a mean age of approximately 50&nbsp;years, with low back pain lasting at least 3&nbsp;months and MCs on MRI, were randomized in a 1:1&nbsp;ratio to receive either a single 5
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;mg IV infusion of zoledronic acid or placebo. MCs were determined on MRI performed within 6&nbsp;months prior to enrollment. Other inclusion criteria included pain intensity of at least 6 cm on a 10
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;cm VAS or an Oswestry Disability Index, or ODI, of at least 30%. Low back pain intensity was measured at screening and 1&nbsp;and 12&nbsp;months after infusion using a 10
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;cm VAS. The primary outcome was the change in low back pain intensity as measured by the VAS. Pain medication use was inquired about during study visits.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	Study participants had a mean low back pain duration of 293&nbsp;days at study entry, and initial low back pain intensity of&nbsp;6.7 on the VAS. All patients displayed either type&nbsp;1, type&nbsp;2, or mixed type&nbsp;1 and type&nbsp;2 MCs on MRI. There was a statistically significant reduction in pain intensity, measured using the VAS, at 1&nbsp;month in the zoledronic acid
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;treated group as compared to placebo. Changes in pain intensity at 12&nbsp;months were numerically greater in the zoledronic acid arm than in the placebo arm but were not statistically significant.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	At 1&nbsp;year only 20% of patients in the zoledronic acid treatment group reported using NSAIDs compared to 60% of patients in the placebo group. At baseline, there were no differences in self
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;reported use of NSAIDs between the treatment groups.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	The most commonly reported adverse events were acute phase reactions, which occurred more frequently in the zoledronic acid
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;treated group. The majority of the acute phase reactions were rated mild to moderate in severity and typically resolved within three days of onset. Sinusitis requiring temporary hospitalization following zoledronic acid infusion was reported in one patient and was therefore classified as a serious adverse event.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Ongoing and Planned Phase&nbsp;3 Trials of AXS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	&#8209;02 in CRPS
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">
	Ongoing CREATE
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">
	&#8209;1 Study
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	In July&nbsp;2015, we initiated the CREATE
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;1 study, a Phase&nbsp;3, randomized, double
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;blind, placebo
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;controlled trial to assess the efficacy and safety of AXS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;02 in the treatment of pain associated with CRPS. Eligible patients must be at least 18&nbsp;years of age, with recently diagnosed CRPS type&nbsp;1 according to the International Association for the Study of Pain, or IASP, diagnostic criteria, and an average weekly baseline pain intensity in the affected limb of at least&nbsp;5 on an 11
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;point (0
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;10) numeric rating scale, or NRS. In addition, the CRPS must have been precipitated by traumatic injury to the affected limb, for example, fracture, crushing injury, or orthopedic surgery. We expect to complete this trial by the end of&nbsp;2017.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
</P>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-LEFT:10.2941176470588%;MARGIN-RIGHT:10.2941176470588%;">
<P>
<FONT SIZE="1">
</FONT>
</P>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:24PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	15
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
</P>
</DIV>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-LEFT:10.2941176470588%;MARGIN-RIGHT:10.2941176470588%;">
<HR ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE='BACKGROUND-COLOR:#000000; BORDER-WIDTH:0; COLOR:#000000; HEIGHT:2PT; LINEHEIGHT:0; WIDTH:100%;'>
<P STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage16"></A>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-LEFT:10.2941176470588%;MARGIN-RIGHT:10.2941176470588%;">
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 30PT;COLOR:#0563C1;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<A HREF="#AXSM-20151231X10KA_HTM_TOC">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;COLOR:#0563C1;">
	Table of Contents
</FONT>
</A>
</P>
</DIV>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-LEFT:10.2941176470588%;MARGIN-RIGHT:10.2941176470588%;">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	After a baseline period, patients meeting the entry criteria will be randomly assigned in a 1:1&nbsp;ratio to orally receive either (1)&nbsp;AXS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;02 tablets once per week for 6&nbsp;weeks, or (2)&nbsp;matching placebo tablets once per week for 6&nbsp;weeks. Patients will receive drug or placebo under fasting conditions, which is typical for oral bisphosphonates. Randomized patients will remain blinded for an additional 6&nbsp;weeks, totaling 12&nbsp;weeks for the double
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;blind phase. The primary endpoint will be the change in pain intensity from baseline to week&nbsp;12, measured using the NRS. Patients will be followed for an additional 12&nbsp;weeks after the double
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;blind period. We anticipate that the study will enroll a total of approximately 190&nbsp;patients. An interim analysis for efficacy is planned on the first approximately 50% of patients who are enrolled and who complete the double
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;blind phase, and is anticipated around the end of 2016.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">
	Additional Planned Phase&nbsp;3 Trial in CRPS
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	We plan to conduct a second Phase&nbsp;3 trial in patients with recently diagnosed CRPS. The design and entry criteria for this trial will be similar to those of the CREATE
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;1 trial with the exception that it will incorporate three treatment arms instead of two. After a baseline period, patients meeting the entry criteria will be randomized in a 1:1:1&nbsp;ratio to receive either (1)&nbsp;AXS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;02 tablets once per week for 6&nbsp;weeks, (2)&nbsp;AXS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;02 tablets once per week for 3&nbsp;weeks and matching placebo tablets for the following 3&nbsp;weeks, or (3)&nbsp;matching placebo tablets once per week for 6&nbsp;weeks. Randomized patients will remain blinded for an additional 6&nbsp;weeks, totaling 12&nbsp;weeks for the double
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;blind phase. The primary endpoint will be the change in pain intensity from baseline to week&nbsp;12, measured using the NRS. We anticipate that the trial will enroll a total of approximately 285 patients.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Planned Phase&nbsp;3 Trial in the Pain of Knee OA Associated with BMLs, the COAST
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	&#8209;1 Study
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	We intend to initiate a Phase&nbsp;3, randomized, double
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;blind, placebo
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;controlled trial to assess the efficacy and safety of AXS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;02 in the treatment of the pain of knee OA associated with BMLs, which we refer to as the COAST
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;1 study. This trial is anticipated to enroll approximately 346&nbsp;patients with clinically diagnosed knee OA and at least one confirmed BML in the affected knee on MRI. Eligible patients must be at least 50&nbsp;years of age, either male or postmenopausal female, and have at least moderate pain intensity. After a baseline period, patients meeting the entry criteria will be randomized in a 1:1&nbsp;ratio to receive either (1)&nbsp;AXS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;02 tablets once per week or (2)&nbsp;matching placebo tablets once per week, under fasting conditions for 6&nbsp;weeks. Randomized patients will remain blinded for an additional 18&nbsp;weeks, totaling 24&nbsp;weeks for the double
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;blind phase. The primary endpoint is anticipated to be the change in pain intensity from baseline to week&nbsp;24, measured using the NRS. We plan to initiate this trial in the first quarter of&nbsp;2016.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Planned Phase&nbsp;3 Trial in CLBP Associated with MCs
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	We intend to initiate a Phase&nbsp;3, randomized, double
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;blind, placebo
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;controlled trial to assess the efficacy and safety of AXS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;02 in the treatment of CLBP associated with MCs. This trial is anticipated to enroll patients with low back pain lasting at least 3&nbsp;months and confirmed type 1 or mixed type 1 and type 2&nbsp;MCs on MRI. After a baseline period, patients meeting the entry criteria will be randomized in a 1:1&nbsp;ratio to receive either (1)&nbsp;AXS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;02 tablets once per week or (2)&nbsp;matching placebo tablets once per week, under fasting conditions for 6&nbsp;weeks. Randomized patients will remain blinded for an additional 6&nbsp;weeks, totaling 12&nbsp;weeks for the double
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;blind phase. The primary endpoint is anticipated to be the change in pain intensity from baseline to week&nbsp;12, measured using the NRS. We anticipate that the trial will enroll a total of approximately 300 patients. We plan to initiate this trial in the fourth quarter of&nbsp;2016 or the first quarter of 2017.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	AXS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	&#8209;05
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Overview
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	AXS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;05 is an innovative fixed
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;dose combination of dextromethorphan and bupropion under development for the treatment of CNS disorders. DM is active at multiple CNS receptors but is rapidly metabolized into dextrorphan, or DXO, when dosed alone. Our combination uses bupropion as a novel drug delivery method to inhibit DM metabolism and increase its bioavailability. Bupropion itself is also active at distinct CNS receptors. The activity of the two components may provide an additive or synergistic effect.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
</P>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-LEFT:10.2941176470588%;MARGIN-RIGHT:10.2941176470588%;">
<P>
<FONT SIZE="1">
</FONT>
</P>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:24PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	16
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
</P>
</DIV>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-LEFT:10.2941176470588%;MARGIN-RIGHT:10.2941176470588%;">
<HR ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE='BACKGROUND-COLOR:#000000; BORDER-WIDTH:0; COLOR:#000000; HEIGHT:2PT; LINEHEIGHT:0; WIDTH:100%;'>
<P STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage17"></A>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-LEFT:10.2941176470588%;MARGIN-RIGHT:10.2941176470588%;">
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 30PT;COLOR:#0563C1;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<A HREF="#AXSM-20151231X10KA_HTM_TOC">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;COLOR:#0563C1;">
	Table of Contents
</FONT>
</A>
</P>
</DIV>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-LEFT:10.2941176470588%;MARGIN-RIGHT:10.2941176470588%;">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	AXS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;05 is potentially applicable to the treatment of a variety of CNS disorders, based on the mechanisms of action of its two components. We are developing AXS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;05 initially as a therapeutic for treatment resistant depression and agitation in patients with Alzheimer&#x2019;s disease.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Scientific Rationale
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
<IMG SRC="http://content.edgar-online.com/edgar_conv_img/2016/08/09/0001558370-16-007797_AXSM20151231X10KA002.JPG" STYLE="WIDTH: 5.5IN; HEIGHT: 3.055553IN" ALT="PICTURE 3">
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	DM and bupropion each target different CNS receptor systems that are potentially relevant to the treatment of CNS disorders. Combining the distinct and independent mechanisms of action of these two compounds may be additive or synergistic in the treatment of depression and other CNS disorders. However, as shown in the figure above, DM is quickly eliminated from the body following administration due to extensive first pass metabolism, which results in low blood levels even at high doses. Attainment of potential therapeutic plasma levels of DM is therefore difficult when DM is dosed as a single agent. We have demonstrated in two Phase&nbsp;1 trials that co
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;administration of bupropion and DM leads to substantially increased DM plasma levels. This positive pharmacokinetic interaction between bupropion and DM therefore may enable DM&#x2019;s clinical utility by increasing DM&#x2019;s plasma levels into a potentially therapeutic range. We believe this dual pharmacodynamic and pharmacokinetic synergy results in a unique pharmacological profile that could potentially be efficacious in CNS disorders.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	Bupropion is a well
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;characterized antidepressant that is chemically unrelated to tricyclic, tetracyclic, selective serotonin reuptake inhibitor, or other known antidepressant agents. It is an inhibitor of the neuronal uptake of norepinephrine and dopamine, and does not inhibit monoamine oxidase or the reuptake of serotonin. It is the only antidepressant currently available that is capable of selectively inhibiting both dopamine and norepinephrine reuptake. Bupropion was approved in the United States in&nbsp;1985 and is marketed under the trade name Wellbutrin for the treatment of major depressive disorder, or MDD, and under the trade name Zyban as an aid to smoking cessation.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	DM is a noncompetitive N
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;methyl
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;D
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;aspartate, or NMDA, receptor antagonist, a sigma
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;1 receptor agonist, and an inhibitor of the serotonin transporter, or SERT, and norepinephrine transporter, or NET. Each of these mechanisms of action has been shown to be associated with antidepressant response. DM is a well
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;known agent that is used as an ingredient in over
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;the
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;counter cough and cold preparations. DM, in combination with quinidine, was approved by the FDA in&nbsp;2010 for the treatment of pseudobulbar affect, also known as emotional lability. Like bupropion in our product candidate, quinidine is used to inhibit the metabolism of DM and increase its plasma concentrations. Unlike bupropion, however, the quinidine in the preparation does not have CNS activity.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
</FONT>
</P>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-LEFT:10.2941176470588%;MARGIN-RIGHT:10.2941176470588%;">
<P>
<FONT SIZE="1">
</FONT>
</P>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:24PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	17
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
</P>
</DIV>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-LEFT:10.2941176470588%;MARGIN-RIGHT:10.2941176470588%;">
<HR ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE='BACKGROUND-COLOR:#000000; BORDER-WIDTH:0; COLOR:#000000; HEIGHT:2PT; LINEHEIGHT:0; WIDTH:100%;'>
<P STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage18"></A>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-LEFT:10.2941176470588%;MARGIN-RIGHT:10.2941176470588%;">
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 30PT;COLOR:#0563C1;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<A HREF="#AXSM-20151231X10KA_HTM_TOC">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;COLOR:#0563C1;">
	Table of Contents
</FONT>
</A>
</P>
</DIV>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-LEFT:10.2941176470588%;MARGIN-RIGHT:10.2941176470588%;">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Treatment Resistant Depression (TRD)
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	We are developing AXS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;05 for the treatment of TRD. Currently only one product, Symbyax, a combination of olanzapine and fluoxetine, which is marketed by Eli Lilly and Company, is approved in the United States for the treatment of TRD.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Indication Overview
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	Patients diagnosed with MDD are defined as having TRD if they have failed two or more antidepressant therapies. MDD is a serious condition characterized by depressed mood or a loss of interest or pleasure in daily activities consistently for at least a two
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;week period, and which impairs social, occupational, educational, or other important functioning. MDD is highly prevalent and difficult to treat. According to the National Institute of Health, or NIH, an estimated 6.7% of U.S. adults experience MDD each year, while 3.3% of individuals 13&nbsp;to 18&nbsp;years of age experience a seriously debilitating depressive disorder. Results of the Sequenced Treatment Alternatives to Relieve Depression, or STAR*D trial, funded by the National Institute of Mental Health, indicate that nearly two
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;thirds of diagnosed and treated patients do not experience adequate treatment response with first
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;line therapy, and that the majority of these initial failures also fail second
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;line treatment. Based on these observations, we estimate that there are approximately 3&nbsp;million patients with TRD in the United States.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Rationale for the Use of AXS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	&#8209;05 in TRD
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	The rationale for the use of AXS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;05 in TRD is based on the mechanisms of action of DM, preclinical evidence of antidepressant effects of DM, preliminary clinical evidence of antidepressant effects of DM when co
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;administered with an inhibitor of its metabolism, and the established clinical efficacy of bupropion in&nbsp;MDD.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Mechanistic rationale.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&nbsp;DM&#x2019;s mechanisms of action encompass those of several currently marketed antidepressant drugs such as duloxetine (Cymbalta), fluoxetine (Prozac), and fluvoxamine (Luvox). Bupropion inhibits the reuptake of dopamine and is a nicotinic acetylocholine receptor antagonist. The distinct mechanisms of action of DM and bupropion may therefore be complementary. Additionally we believe that, if successfully developed, the NMDA receptor antagonist properties of DM in AXS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;05 may potentially result in a faster onset of action than currently available antidepressant treatments.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Preclinical rationale.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&nbsp;The effects of DM have been reported in two preclinical models of antidepressant effect. In the forced swim test model in mice, DM administered intraperitoneally resulted in antidepressant
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;like effects in a dose
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;dependent manner. The forced swim test is considered to be the most well
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;validated animal model for predicting antidepressant effect. Using the tail suspension test in mice, another widely used behavioral test for assessing antidepressant potential, DM was also shown to display antidepressant
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;like effects similar to those seen with imipramine, a conventional antidepressant, and ketamine, a compound that has demonstrated fast
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;acting antidepressant effects. In both models, inhibition of DM metabolism using quinidine was shown to potentiate the antidepressant
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;like effects.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Clinical Rationale.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&nbsp;Administration of DM with an inhibitor of its metabolism has been shown to reduce depressive symptoms, measured using the Beck Depression Inventory Second Edition, or BDI
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;II, in a third
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;party study. In a 326
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;patient, randomized, double
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;blind, placebo
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;controlled trial in patients with pseudobulbar affect, co
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;administration of DM and the metabolic inhibitor quinidine resulted in a statistically significant reduction in depressive symptoms as compared to placebo at the 30&nbsp;mg&nbsp;DM&nbsp;/ 10&nbsp;mg quinidine dose at 12&nbsp;weeks. Patients were excluded from the study if their BDI
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;II score was greater than 19, with a score in the range of 0 to 13 corresponding to minimal depression and 14 to 19 corresponding to mild depression. Assessment of depressive symptoms was a pre
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;specified secondary endpoint in this trial.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	According to the FDA package insert for the combination of DM and quinidine (Nuedexta), DM is the pharmacologically active ingredient of the DM / quinidine combination that acts on the CNS, with quinidine serving to increase DM plasma levels. The plasma concentrations of DM, measured using AUC
</FONT>
<SUB STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	0
</SUB>
<SUB STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;12
</SUB>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	and C
</FONT>
<SUB STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	max
</SUB>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	, achieved with AXS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;05 administration in our Phase&nbsp;1 trials are in the range of those associated with a 30&nbsp;mg&nbsp;DM&nbsp;/ 10&nbsp;mg quinidine dose, based on data published by the FDA.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
</FONT>
</P>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-LEFT:10.2941176470588%;MARGIN-RIGHT:10.2941176470588%;">
<P>
<FONT SIZE="1">
</FONT>
</P>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:24PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	18
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
</P>
</DIV>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-LEFT:10.2941176470588%;MARGIN-RIGHT:10.2941176470588%;">
<HR ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE='BACKGROUND-COLOR:#000000; BORDER-WIDTH:0; COLOR:#000000; HEIGHT:2PT; LINEHEIGHT:0; WIDTH:100%;'>
<P STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage19"></A>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-LEFT:10.2941176470588%;MARGIN-RIGHT:10.2941176470588%;">
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 30PT;COLOR:#0563C1;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<A HREF="#AXSM-20151231X10KA_HTM_TOC">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;COLOR:#0563C1;">
	Table of Contents
</FONT>
</A>
</P>
</DIV>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-LEFT:10.2941176470588%;MARGIN-RIGHT:10.2941176470588%;">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Agitation in Patients with Alzheimer&#x2019;s Disease (AD)
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	We intend to develop AXS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;05 for the treatment of agitation in patients with AD. There is currently no FDA
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;approved pharmacological treatment for the indication of agitation in patients with AD.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Indication Overview
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	AD is a progressive neurodegenerative disorder that manifests initially as forgetfulness advancing to severe cognitive impairment and memory loss. It is a common form of dementia and afflicts an estimated 5&nbsp;million individuals in the United States, a number that is anticipated to increase to approximately 14&nbsp;million by 2050. In addition to cognitive decline, individuals diagnosed with AD typically experience behavioral and psychological symptoms including agitation and aggression. These symptoms are seen in a high percentage of AD sufferers with agitation being reported in as many as 40% of patients. Agitation is characterized by emotional distress, aggressive behaviors, disruptive irritability, and disinhibition. Agitation in patients with AD has been associated with increased caregiver burden, decreased functioning, earlier nursing home placement, and death.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	Because there are no FDA
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;approved pharmacological treatments for the indication of agitation in patients with AD, patients are currently treated off
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;label with various agents including antipsychotics, which have been considered the mainstay of treatment. These treatments however are limited by safety concerns. Typical antipsychotics prescribed for agitation, aggression, or insomnia are associated with functional decline in patients with AD, while studies indicate that atypical antipsychotics may be associated with increased rates of cerebrovascular events in patients with dementia.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Rationale for the Development of AXS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	&#8209;05 in Agitation in Patients with AD
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	The rationale for the use of AXS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;05 for the treatment of agitation in patients with AD is based on the mechanisms of action of DM, and preliminary clinical evidence of the effect of DM when co
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;administered with an inhibitor of its metabolism in agitation in patients with AD.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Mechanistic rationale.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&nbsp;Mechanisms of action of DM include NMDA receptor antagonism and sigma
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;1 receptor agonism. Altered glutamate transmission via NMDA receptors has been suggested to play a role in behavioral changes in dementia, and clinical evidence suggests that NMDA antagonism may reduce agitation and aggression in AD patients. The pharmacologic action of agents used in the treatment of dementia, such as donepezil, and behavioral disorders, such as fluvoxamine, include sigma
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;1 receptor agonism.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Clinical Rationale.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&nbsp;Administration of DM with an inhibitor of its metabolism has been shown to result in a statistically significant reduction in agitation in patients with AD. The effects of DM co
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;administered with the metabolic inhibitor quinidine was studied in a third
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;party, randomized, double
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;blind, placebo
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;controlled, two
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;stage trial in 220 patients with probable AD and clinically meaningful agitation. In stage&nbsp;1 of the study, patients were randomized to receive either placebo or DM with quinidine (20&nbsp;mg&nbsp;DM&nbsp;/ 10&nbsp;mg quinidine once per day, titrated to 30&nbsp;mg&nbsp;DM&nbsp;/ 10&nbsp;mg quinidine twice per day). In stage&nbsp;2, patients initially on placebo were stratified according to response, then re
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;randomized to placebo or active treatment (titrated as in stage&nbsp;1). Each stage lasted five weeks. The primary endpoint was the change in the agitation/aggression domain of the Neuropsychiatric Inventory, or NPI, assessed by combining results from the two stages.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
</P>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-LEFT:10.2941176470588%;MARGIN-RIGHT:10.2941176470588%;">
<P>
<FONT SIZE="1">
</FONT>
</P>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:24PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	19
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
</P>
</DIV>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-LEFT:10.2941176470588%;MARGIN-RIGHT:10.2941176470588%;">
<HR ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE='BACKGROUND-COLOR:#000000; BORDER-WIDTH:0; COLOR:#000000; HEIGHT:2PT; LINEHEIGHT:0; WIDTH:100%;'>
<P STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage20"></A>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-LEFT:10.2941176470588%;MARGIN-RIGHT:10.2941176470588%;">
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 30PT;COLOR:#0563C1;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<A HREF="#AXSM-20151231X10KA_HTM_TOC">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;COLOR:#0563C1;">
	Table of Contents
</FONT>
</A>
</P>
</DIV>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-LEFT:10.2941176470588%;MARGIN-RIGHT:10.2941176470588%;">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	The primary endpoint showed a statistically significant improvement with DM and quinidine as compared to placebo. A statistically significantly greater reduction in the agitation/aggression domain of the NPI for active treatment as compared to placebo was seen in both stage&nbsp;1 as well as in stage&nbsp;2 of the study. An experimental result, such as those derived from a clinical or non-clinical study, is statistically significant if it is unlikely to have occurred by chance. The statistical significance of experimental results is determined by a widely used statistical method that establishes the P value of the results. A P value is a statistical measure of the probability that the difference in results between treatment and control groups in a study could have occurred by chance. Under this method, the smaller the P value the greater the confidence that the results are significant, and a P value of 0.05 or less is generally considered by the FDA to represent statistical significance. During stage&nbsp;1, a reduction of 3.3 in the agitation/aggression domain of the NPI was seen for active treatment as compared to a reduction of 1.7 for placebo, with a P value that is less than 0.001. During stage&nbsp;2, a reduction of 2.0 was observed for active treatment as compared to a reduction of 0.8 for placebo, with a P value that is equal to 0.02. Average baseline values for the agitation/aggression domain of the NPI were 7.1 for the active treatment group and 7.0 for the placebo group. Statistically significant improvements for the active treatment arm compared to placebo were also reported for the majority of secondary endpoints including the NPI total score, NPI
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;Caregiver Distress Score, Caregiver Strain Index, and Cornell Scale for Depression in Dementia. Moreover, treatment with DM and the metabolic inhibitor was not associated with cognitive decline as measured by the Mini Mental State Examination.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	In the trial, patients were titrated to a 30&nbsp;mg&nbsp;DM&nbsp;/ 10&nbsp;mg quinidine dose. According to the FDA package insert for Nuedexta, DM is the pharmacologically active ingredient of the DM&nbsp;/ quinidine combination that acts on the CNS, with quinidine serving to increase DM plasma levels. The plasma concentrations of DM, measured using AUC
</FONT>
<SUB STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	0
</SUB>
<SUB STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;12
</SUB>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	and C
</FONT>
<SUB STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	max
</SUB>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	, achieved with AXS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;05 administration in our Phase&nbsp;1 trials are in the range of those associated with a 30&nbsp;mg&nbsp;DM&nbsp;/ 10&nbsp;mg quinidine dose, based on data published by the FDA.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Clinical Development of AXS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	&#8209;05
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	We are developing AXS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;05 and intend to seek FDA approval for the product utilizing the 505(b)(2) regulatory pathway. We have completed two Phase&nbsp;1 pharmacokinetic clinical trials of AXS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;05 under clinical trial applications with Health Canada. In both studies, administration of bupropion in combination with DM resulted in a substantial increase in DM plasma concentrations measured using C
</FONT>
<SUB STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	max
</SUB>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	and AUC at all doses tested.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	We held a pre
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;IND meeting with the FDA in February 2015 where we discussed our clinical development plan for AXS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;05 in TRD. Based on that meeting, we submitted an investigational new drug application, or IND, to the FDA and we plan to conduct two Phase&nbsp;3 trials of AXS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;05 in TRD to support an NDA filing for this indication.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	In March 2016, we initiated the STRIDE-1 study, a Phase&nbsp;3, randomized, double
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;blind, active
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;controlled trial to assess the efficacy and safety of AXS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;05 in the treatment of TRD. We plan to meet with the FDA this year to discuss our plans to conduct a controlled trial of AXS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;05 in agitation in patients with AD.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Completed Phase&nbsp;1 Trials of AXS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	&#8209;05
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	We have completed two Phase&nbsp;1 pharmacokinetic clinical trials of AXS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;05. The objectives of these trials were to assess the pharmacokinetics of DM when co
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;administered with bupropion, and to assess the safety and tolerability of the combination. In these Phase&nbsp;1 trials, the components of AXS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;05, DM and bupropion, were co
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;administered as separate tablets. In both studies, administration of bupropion in combination with DM resulted in substantial increases in DM plasma concentrations measured using C
</FONT>
<SUB STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	max
</SUB>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	and AUC at all doses tested.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
</P>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-LEFT:10.2941176470588%;MARGIN-RIGHT:10.2941176470588%;">
<P>
<FONT SIZE="1">
</FONT>
</P>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:24PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	20
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
</P>
</DIV>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-LEFT:10.2941176470588%;MARGIN-RIGHT:10.2941176470588%;">
<HR ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE='BACKGROUND-COLOR:#000000; BORDER-WIDTH:0; COLOR:#000000; HEIGHT:2PT; LINEHEIGHT:0; WIDTH:100%;'>
<P STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage21"></A>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-LEFT:10.2941176470588%;MARGIN-RIGHT:10.2941176470588%;">
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 30PT;COLOR:#0563C1;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<A HREF="#AXSM-20151231X10KA_HTM_TOC">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;COLOR:#0563C1;">
	Table of Contents
</FONT>
</A>
</P>
</DIV>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-LEFT:10.2941176470588%;MARGIN-RIGHT:10.2941176470588%;">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	The first Phase&nbsp;1 trial was a randomized, multiple
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;dose, open
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;label study to determine the pharmacokinetics of DM when various doses of DM are administered concomitantly with bupropion under fasting conditions, as well as the safety of the combination. Subjects were randomized to receive twice
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;daily administrations of 150&nbsp;mg of bupropion in combination with DM at various doses up to 60&nbsp;mg, or 60&nbsp;mg of DM alone, for 8 consecutive days. Bupropion was titrated with subjects being dosed once daily for the first 3 days, then twice daily thereafter. A total of 32 healthy, adult volunteers were included in this study in four treatment groups. Full pharmacokinetic assessments were made on Day&nbsp;1 and Day&nbsp;8. For the dose of 60&nbsp;mg of DM&nbsp;/ 150&nbsp;mg of bupropion, AUC
</FONT>
<SUB STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	0
</SUB>
<SUB STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;12
</SUB>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	and C
</FONT>
<SUB STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	max
</SUB>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	values on Day&nbsp;8 for DM when dosed in combination with bupropion were approximately 60 times and 40 times, respectively, the values for DM when dosed alone. For all doses tested, administration of DM in combination with bupropion resulted in substantial increases in AUC
</FONT>
<SUB STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	0
</SUB>
<SUB STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;12
</SUB>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	and C
</FONT>
<SUB STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	max
</SUB>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	values of DM on Day&nbsp;8 as compared to Day&nbsp;1 of dosing. DM exposure measured using AUC and C
</FONT>
<SUB STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	max
</SUB>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	increased in a dose dependent manner with increasing doses of DM. Administration of DM did not appear to affect the pharmacokinetics of bupropion.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	There were no reported serious adverse events in the trial. The majority of treatment
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;emergent adverse events experienced were graded as mild or moderate in severity, and had resolved by the end of the study. The most commonly reported adverse events were dizziness, nausea, headache, insomnia, dry mouth, constipation, hypoesthesia, palpitation, disturbance in attention, tremor, and hyperhidrosis. Adverse events were reported more frequently in the AXS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;05 arm as compared to the DM
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;only arm. The majority of these adverse events were expected with the administration of bupropion, having been already reported in the FDA package inserts for products containing bupropion.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	The second Phase&nbsp;1 trial was a randomized, multiple
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;dose, open
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;label study to determine the pharmacokinetics of DM when various doses of DM are administered concomitantly with various doses of bupropion and to assess safety during co
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;administration of bupropion and DM. A total of 40 healthy, adult volunteers were included in this study in five treatment groups. Subjects were randomized to receive twice
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;daily administration of either 150&nbsp;mg of bupropion alone, or combinations of varying doses of bupropion and DM for 8 consecutive days. Bupropion was titrated with subjects being dosed once daily for the first 3 days, then twice daily thereafter. Full pharmacokinetic assessments were made on Day&nbsp;1 and Day&nbsp;8. Similar to the results in our first study, administration of DM in combination with bupropion resulted in substantial increases in AUC
</FONT>
<SUB STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	0
</SUB>
<SUB STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&#8209;12
</SUB>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	and C
</FONT>
<SUB STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	max
</SUB>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	values of DM on Day&nbsp;8 as compared to Day&nbsp;1 of dosing for all combinations tested. DM exposure measured using AUC and C
</FONT>
<SUB STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	max
</SUB>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	increased in a dose
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
